\begin_layout Subsection
Sampling:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sampling is an important concept in digital signal processing.
 It is the process of creating a discrete-time signal from a known continuous-ti
me signal by sampling it at regular time intervals.
 Also, all the digital devices and computers we use can perform arithmetic
 and algorithms only on discrete data.
 Hence, sampling is a very important concept in signal processing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Let's say the CT signal is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Now the sampled DT signal will be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x[n]=x_{c}(t)|_{t=nT_{s}}=x_{c}(nT_{s})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}$
\end_inset

 is known as sampling period.
 The associated sampling frequency is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ùõ∫_{s}=\frac{2\pi}{T_{s}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
(In this report, ùõ∫ denotes frequency in CT signals and ùúî denotes frequency
 in DT signals)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nyquist-Shannon sampling theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever we sample a CT signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

 and obtain a DT signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset

, their spectra: 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{c}(ùõ∫)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X(ùúî)$
\end_inset

 are related as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X(ùúî)=\frac{1}{T_{s}}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}X_{c}(\frac{ùúî}{T_{s}}-k\frac{2\pi}{T_{s}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Now, the Nyquist-Shannon sampling theorem states:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a bandlimited signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

, the sampling frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{s}$
\end_inset

 should be atleast twice the maximum frequency present in the spectrum of
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

 in order to prevent overlapping (or Aliasing).
 Only if this condition is satisfied, the DTFT of 
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset

 will preserve the original information about the CT signal.
 A visual representation is shown below:
\end_layout

