\begin_layout Subsection
Digital fourier transform:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Digital fourier transform (DFT) is an important concept in digital signal
 processing.
 As we already saw, we have a continuous variable spectrum pertaining to
 DT signals known as Dsicrete-time fourier transform (DTFT) which is given
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X(w)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}x[n]e^{-jwn}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
This is a real variable function and is defined for a continuum of values.
 DFT, on the other hand, is a discrete variable signal and is defined only
 for certain integer values.
 Let's assume we have an N-periodic DT signal, i.e., if we know its first
 N samples 
\begin_inset Formula $(x[0],x[1],...x[N-1])$
\end_inset

, we know the full signal.
 Now, its DFT is defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a[k]=\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}x[n]e^{-j\frac{2\pi}{N}kn}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x[n]=\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\frac{a[k]}{N}e^{j\frac{2\pi}{N}kn}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
and both
\series default
 
\series medium
k and n belong to the set 
\begin_inset Formula ${0,1,2,...N-1}.$
\end_inset

 Also, the DT signal x[n] calculated by the inverse DFT formula is inherently
 periodic with period 'N'.
 Hence, DFT is usually used to analyse periodic DT signals.
 Their values present in one single period contains all information about
 that signal and its DFT.
 Note that both 
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset

 and its DFT 
\begin_inset Formula $a[k]$
\end_inset

 are periodic with period as 'N' samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Connection between CTFT and DFT:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's say we have a finite length CT signal and this signal, when periodically
 extended and sampled, gives us a DT signal.
 Let us define the following functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 = Finite length CT signal of length 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X_{fin}(ùõ∫)$
\end_inset

 = CTFT of 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

 = Periodic extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 with period 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{0}$
\end_inset

= Fundamental frequency of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

 = 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\pi}{T_{0}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

= 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 CTFS coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X_{c}(ùõ∫)$
\end_inset

 = CTFT of periodic CT signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset

 = Sampled version of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(nT_{s})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{s}$
\end_inset

= Sampling frequency = 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\pi}{T_{s}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $ùúî_{o}$
\end_inset

= DFT resolution frequency = 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\pi}{N}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X(ùúî)$
\end_inset

 = DTFT of signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $a[k]$
\end_inset

 = 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 DFT coefficient of signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Let's assume the first N samples that define 
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset

 are given by sampling the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{o}$
\end_inset

 period signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t).$
\end_inset

 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}=\frac{T_{0}}{N}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have the following 
\series bold
important
\series default
 equations which relate the spectra of CT signal and the sampled DT signal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{fin}(kùõ∫_{o})=T_{o}a_{k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{c}(ùõ∫)=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi a_{k}\delta(ùõ∫-kùõ∫_{o})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X(\omega)=\frac{1}{T_{s}}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}X_{c}(\frac{\omega}{T_{s}}-k\frac{2\pi}{T_{s}})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X(ùúî)=\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\frac{2\pi a[k]}{N}ùõø(ùúî-kùúî_{o})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
(The last equation relates the DTFT and DFT of periodic DT signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x[n]$
\end_inset

 in the first period [-
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

).)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let's assume that the CTFT of the periodic CT signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{c}(t)$
\end_inset

 is bandlimited (or) atleast has a decreasing trend in the fourier series
 coefficients such that we can assume that the spectrum is approximately
 bandlimited after a particular value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Now, we can choose a sampling frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{s}$
\end_inset

 such that the Nyquist criteria is met, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{s}>2ùõ∫_{m}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the maximum frequency component present in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{c}(ùõ∫).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Any CT frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫$
\end_inset

 we have will become 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫T_{s}$
\end_inset

 in the DT domain.
 Hence, a freqeuncy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ùõ∫_{s}}{2}$
\end_inset

 in CT domain becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ùõ∫_{s}T_{s}}{2}=\pi$
\end_inset

 in the DT domain.
 So, a range of [
\begin_inset Formula $-ùõ∫_{s}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{s}$
\end_inset

) in CT domain becomes [-
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

) in the DT domain.
 Also, since the Nyquist criteria is assumed to be satisfied, we can safely
 say:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X(\omega)=\frac{1}{T_{s}}X_{c}(\frac{\omega}{T_{s}})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
for 
\begin_inset Formula $ùúî\in[-\pi,\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 We are able to get this equation only because Nyquist criteria is satisfied.
 Else, the shifted spectrum terms will also contribute to 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\omega).$
\end_inset

With this assumption, let's see how 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\omega)$
\end_inset

 will be related to the DFT coefficients.
 From equation 
\begin_inset Formula $(4),(5),$
\end_inset

we can say:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{c}(\frac{ùúî}{T_{s}})=\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\frac{2\pi.T_{s}.a[k]}{N}ùõø(ùúî-kùúî_{o})=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi a_{k}\delta(\frac{ùúî}{T_{s}}-k\frac{2\pi}{T_{o}})=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}2\pi.T_{s}.a_{k}\delta(ùúî-k\frac{2\pi}{N})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Since, we have assumed that the CTFS coefficients are limited within [-
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ùõ∫_{s}}{2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{ùõ∫_{s}}{2}$
\end_inset

) in the CT domain, they will be restricted in [-
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

) on the DT domain (or) the w-axis.
 So, our eqn.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(6)$
\end_inset

 reduces to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{k=-\frac{N}{2}}^{\frac{N}{2}-1}\frac{2\pi.T_{s}.a[k]}{N}ùõø(ùúî-kùúî_{o})=\sum_{k=-\frac{N}{2}}^{\frac{N}{2}-1}2\pi.T_{s}.a_{k}\delta(ùúî-k\frac{2\pi}{N})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Clearly, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{k}=\frac{a[k]}{N}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we also have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{fin}(kùõ∫_{o})=T_{o}a_{k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
From eqns.
 
\begin_inset Formula $(7),(8),$
\end_inset

we can say:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{fin}(kùõ∫_{o})=T_{o}\frac{a[k]}{N}=T_{s}a[k]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
The final takeaway point is that if we can safely assume the signal is bandlimit
ed and the sampling frequency satisfies the Nyquist criteria, then the CTFT
 of the finite length CT signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 can be computed at integer values of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõ∫_{o}$
\end_inset

 by multiplying the N-point DFT of the sampled version by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{s}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CT frequency interval : [
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{-\pi.N}{T_{o}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi.N}{T_{o}}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

