\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
We can write this function as a sum of complex exponentials based on the
 
\series default
Laurent's expansion of Bessel's function
\series medium
: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
exp(\frac{\beta}{2}(z-\frac{1}{z}))=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}J_{k}(\beta)z^{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $z=jexp(jw_{m}t)$
\end_inset

, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
exp(j\beta cos(w_{m}t))=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}J_{k}(\beta)j^{k}exp(jkw_{m}t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Now, we have: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cos(w_{c}t+\beta cos(w_{m}t))=Re\{exp(jw_{c}t+j\beta cos(w_{m}t))\}=Re\{e^{jw_{c}t}\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}J_{k}(\beta)e^{j(w_{m}t+\frac{\pi}{2})k}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cos(w_{c}t+\beta cos(w_{m}t))=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}J_{k}(\beta)cos(w_{c}t+kw_{m}t+k\frac{\pi}{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
Writing this as a sum of sinusoids, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cos(w_{c}t+\beta cos(w_{m}t))=\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{J_{k}(\beta)}{2}e^{(w_{c}t+kw_{m}t+k\frac{\pi}{2})}+\sum_{k=-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{J_{k}(\beta)}{2}e^{-(w_{c}t+kw_{m}t+k\frac{\pi}{2})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series medium
